d, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Croxton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places in Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Norfolk, and Staffordshire named Croxton, from the Old Norse personal name <i>Krókr</i> (see   Crook   3) or an Old English word <i>crōc</i> ‘nook’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Crowston","meanings":["English: habitational name from South Croxton or Croxton Kerrial (Leicestershire), traditionally pronounced /'krousən/; or possibly from a village so named in Lincolnshire. Compare   Croxton  ."]},{"name":"Crook","meanings":["English:","topographic name from Old Norse <i>krókr</i> ‘nook or bend’ denoting someone who lived by a bend in a river or road. In some instances the surname may have arisen as a habitational name from any of the places called Crook in Cumberland and Durham, or Crooke in Lancashire, all of which are derived from this word.","topographic name for someone who lived ‘(at the) barrow or mound’ from Brittonic <i>crüg</i>. In some instances this may have arisen as a habitational name from either Crook in Combe Raleigh or perhaps Crooke in North Tawton (both Devon), which are derived from this word."]},{"name":"Croston","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire named Croston, from Old Norse <i>kross</i> ‘cross’ or Old English <i>cros</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","English: occasionally, a variant of   Croxton   or   Croson  ."]}]},{"name":"Martha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, of Aramaic rather than Hebrew origin, meaning ‘lady’. It was borne by the sister of Lazarus and Mary of Bethany (John 11:1). According to Luke 10:38, when Jesus visited the house of Mary and Martha, Mary sat at his feet, listening to him, while Martha ‘was cumbered about much serving’, so that she complained to Jesus, ‘Lord, dost thou not care that my sister hath left me to serve alone?’ For this reason, the name <i>Martha</i> has always been associated with hard domestic work, as opposed to the contemplative life."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Martha Croxton was born in 1469, in Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England. She married Sir John William Nicholas de Carter in 1490, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in December 1514, in her hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1469–December 1514":"1469–detsember 1514","1475–1521":"1475–1521","1495–1544":"1495–1544","1500–1565":"1500–1565","1469–1514":"1469–1514","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1565":"1565","1521":"1521","1475":"1475","1495":"1495","1490":"1490","December 1514":"detsember 1514","Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England":"Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England","Kempston, Bedfordshire, England":"Kempston, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1469–December 1514":"1469–joulukuu 1514","1475–1521":"1475–1521","1495–1544":"1495–1544","1500–1565":"1500–1565","1469–1514":"1469–1514","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1500":"1500","1544":"1544","1565":"1565","1521":"1521","1475":"1475","1495":"1495","1490":"1490","December 1514":"joulukuu 1514","Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England":"Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England","Kempston, Bedfordshire, England":"Kempston, Bedfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1469–December 1514":"1469–décembre 1514","1475–1521":"1475–1521","1495–1544":"1495–1544","1500–1565":"1500–1565","1469–1514":"1469–1514","1514":"1514","1469":"1469","1500":"150